bio: [('Beginning', 'She took up the sport in 1991. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Reason', 'Her parents liked the sport and encouraged her to take lessons. (ITTF You Tube channel, 05 Jan 2016; ittf.org, 15 Feb 2016)'), ('Memorable', "Winning silver in the women's team event at the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)"), ('Awards', "In May 2015 she was inducted into Singapore's Sports Hall of Fame. (todayonline.com, 13 May 2015) In 2014 she was presented with the Singapore Table Tennis Association's [STTA] Player of the Year award. She also won the Excellence in Sports Performance award. (stta.org.sg, 06 Jul 2011)In 2013 she won the STTA's Player of the Year award and was part of the Team of the Year. She was also named the Singapore Sports Award's Player of the Year. (channelnewsasia.com, 28 Feb 2014; stta.org.sg, 06 Jul 2011)She was flag bearer for Singapore at the 2010 Commonwealth Games in Delhi, India. (channelnewsasia.com, 25 Feb 2014)She was awarded the Meritorious Service Medal in recognition of her performance at the 2008 Olympic Games in Beijing. (redsports.sg, 25 Aug 2008)"), ('Additional Information', "GripShakehand (ITTF, 02 Aug 2016)Style of playAttack (ITTF, 02 Aug 2016)GeneralMOVE TO SINGAPOREShe was born in Harbin, People's Republic of China, but moved to Singapore in March 2007 after being scouted by coach Liu Guidong of the Singapore Table Tennis Association [STTA]. She became a Singaporean citizen in January 2008. (theonlinecitizen.com, 13 Aug 2012; tabletennisphotos.com, 08 Feb 2009; tabletennista.com, 16 Apr 2016) "), ('Hero', 'Chinese tennis player Li Na. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Nickname', "Le Le [meaning 'happiness' in Mandarin]. (ITTF, 27 Jul 2012)"), ('Injuries', 'She suffered from knee injuries after the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, and did not recover completely until April 2015. (todayonline.com, 25 Apr 2015) Injury caused her to withdraw from the 2013 National Table Tennis Grand Finale in Singapore. (stta.org.sg, 17 Jan 2014)She has had problems with a long-term injury to her right wrist. name: JIA YI FRANCIS
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began swimming at age five at the Singapore Island Country Club, Singapore. (todayonline.com, 15 Jul 2017)'), ('Reason', 'He was persuaded to go to swimming lessons to overcome his fear of water after being close to drowning after the 2004 Indian Ocean Tsunami. "I was quite traumatised, and I really hated the water, even my brother was quite scared of the water when he was young. My parents used to throw me into the pool, and I would struggle to get back [on land]. But after a while, I embraced it, and really grew to love the sport." (todayonline.com, 15 Jul 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Gary Tan [national] (swimming.org.sg, 30 Jun 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (todayonline.com, 15 Jul 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralTSUNAMI SURVIVORIn December 2004 he was on holiday with his family in Krabi, Thailand, when the resort he was staying in was struck by a tsunami emanating from the Indian Ocean. At age four the waves lifted him and his mother off their feet and his mother managed to hold on to a rock. "We were just hanging out at the beach. I remember it being very chaotic and everything was a mess. We didn\'t know what was going on. I remember my mum grabbing my hand and running to land before we were hit. We were lucky, that first hit pushed us back several metres but as the water receded, we held onto a rock. That rock saved us." The incident left him with a fear of water for a year afterwards. (todayonline.com, 15 Jul 2017) '), ('Nickname', 'Paco (pangshengjun.com, 11 Feb 2015)'), ('Highlights', "RankEventYearLocationResultAsian Championships64 x 200m Freestyle Relay2016Tokyo, JPN7:52.287Men's 4 x 100m Medley Relay2016Tokyo, JPN3:49.288200m Backstroke2016Tokyo, JPN2:07.16Heats50m Backstroke2016Tokyo, JPN26.76Heats100m Backstroke2016Tokyo, JPN57.45Heats4 x 100m Freestyle Relay2016Tokyo, JPN3:39.92South East Asian Games2200m Backstroke2017Kuala Lumpur, MAS2:00.493100m Backstroke2017Kuala Lumpur, MAS55.92550m Backstroke2017Kuala Lumpur, MAS26.10World Championships Short CourseHeats50m Backstroke2016Windsor, ON, CAN26.08Heats100m Backstroke2016Windsor, ON, CAN54.89Heats4 x 50m Medley Relay2016Windsor, ON, CAN1:45.70Heats200m Backstroke2016Windsor, ON, CANDNSHeats4 x 100m Freestyle Relay2016Windsor, ON, CANDNSWorld Junior Championships8Men's 4 x 100m Medley Relay2015Singapore, SIN3:47.40Heats50m Backstroke2015Singapore, SIN26.70Heats100m Backstroke2015Singapore, SIN58.17Heats200m Backstroke2015Singapore, SIN2:07.04Heats4 x 100m Freestyle Relay2015Singapore, SIN3:28.56Heats4 x 200m Freestyle Relay2015Singapore, SIN7:48.24HeatsMixed 4 x 100m Medley Relay2015Singapore, SIN3:59.32")]

name: RU EN ROANNE
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began swimming at age eight. (Athlete, 02 Dec 2006)'), ('Reason', 'Her father signed her and her sister up for water safety classes. (myactivesg.com, 19 Jul 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Gary Tan [national] (tnp.sg, 04 Apr 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning a bronze medal at the 2004 Commonwealth Youth Games in Bendigo, VIC, Australia. (swimming.org.sg, 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralANXIETYAt the conclusion of her events at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia she revealed that she had been struggling with anxiety. "My pain was not poetic, it was days without sleep and pretending I was stable enough to continue. I was so crippled by anxiety, and the fear of being a failure or a disappointment." She revealed it was the outcome of the competition that most affected her. "Sport is so heavily results driven, there will always be a bigger competition or a faster time. That\'s when it hit me, if I felt like I wasn\'t enough without a medal, I would never be enough even with a medal, if I were to base my self worth on my results, I would never be okay with who I am." (asiaone.com, 26 Aug 2018)ROLE MODELShe was determined to return to competitive action and support younger swimmers after suffering a collapsed lung and a shoulder injury in 2016. "When I read stories about people who are injured, most of them either quit or just can\'t get back to where they once were. Every day was a struggle. When I was going through that, I kept thinking if so many people have failed, what makes me think that I can do it? There\'s a younger generation and most of them will get injuries and get their preparations affected, so that\'s my driving purpose right now, to prove that they can still come out on top of whatever happens." (tnp.sg, 04 Apr 2018) '), ('Relatives', 'Her older sister Ruth has also represented Singapore in swimming. (ssc.gov.sg, 23 Feb 2007)'), ('Nickname', 'Ro (Athlete, 02 Dec 2006)'), ('Injuries', 'In April 2016 she suffered a shoulder injury. She underwent surgery in June 2016 and returned to training six weeks later. (straitstimes.com, 03 Sep 2017)In January 2016 she suffered a collapsed lung that kept her from training for a month after surgery. (straitstimes.com, 03 Sep 2017)'), ('Education', 'Marketing - Queensland University of Technology, Brisbane, QLD, AUS'), ('Languages', 'English, Mandarin'), ('Hobbies', 'Watching films and television. name: YWEN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began foil fencing at age six, and took up sabre fencing in 2011. (channelnewsasia.com, 19 Dec 2016)'), ('Reason', 'She followed her older sister into the sport. (myactivesg.com, 2016)'), ('Debut', '2014 for Singapore (asiaone.com, 19 Sep 2014)'), ('Coach', 'David Chan [club], SGP; Min Xinsheng [national], CHN (Fencing Singapore Facebook page, 01 Mar 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the Olympic Games. (channelnewsasia.com, 19 Dec 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralFURTHER EDUCATIONShe has agreed to start studying at Stanford University in California, United States of America, in late 2018. "It was my first choice of university as I feel that I can really fit in, with its extremely diverse community. Fencing is very important to me as well as education, so I\'m very happy for the opportunity to go to a good university and continue my fencing career." (straitstimes.com, 10 Jan 2018; todaysportsupdate.com, 10 Jan 2018)NATIONAL FIRSTShe became the first Singaporean fencer to win a gold medal at the world cadet championships when she claimed victory in the individual sabre at the 2016 edition of the tournament in Bourges, France. (todayonline.com, 2016; SportsDeskOnline, 12 Jun 2018)LONDON EXPERIENCEShe attended the 2012 Olympic Games in London as part of the Champions of Play programme. The scheme gave children from around the world the chance to meet athletes and get behind the scenes of different venues at the event. "The 2012 Olympics were an eye-opener for me. I saw how athletes cope with pressure yet still performed at their best when it was competition time. That taught me how pressure can be channelled positively to your advantage." (asiaone.com, 19 Sep 2014) '), ('Relatives', 'Her older sister Lau Ysien has also represented Singapore in fencing, and placed fifth in team foil at the 2017 Asian Championships in Hong Kong, China. (asiaone.com, 19 Sep 2014; SportsDeskOnline, 12 Jun 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'She could not fence during the fist half of 2017 because of a stress fracture in her back. name: MARK HAN MING
bio: [('Beginning', 'He took up the sport in 2011. (swimming.org.sg, 2014 )'), ('Training', 'He trains for 20 hours. (myactivesg.com, 02 Apr 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To qualify for the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (straitstimes.com, 28 May 2018)'), ('Awards', 'In 2014 he was named Diver of the Year by the Singapore Swimming Association. (voxsports.co, 10 Feb 2014)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralDIVING DOUBLEAlthough he and his twin brother Timothy both represent Singapore in synchronised diving, they were not as close as children. "Growing up, we wanted to create our own identity, so we didn\'t like being around each other." However, they became closer later on and he believes they match well as diving partners. "We complement each other - when he overthinks, I\'m able to help him calm down. And when I take things too lightly, he can bring me up a step." name: Smriti Mahesh
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began athletics training in 2009 in Singapore. (wings.org.sg, 03 Mar 2014)'), ('Reason', 'She began training with her mother\'s personal trainer, Mona. "I was always keen on sports and running, and right from the start I felt like athletics is what I could excel in. Under the guidance of Mona, I began training for athletics in 2009. Mona used to be my mum\'s personal trainer and that\'s how we found out that she used to coach every Sunday at the CCAB [sporting complex], so I decided to start training under her. After a few year of training with Mona, she suggested that I start training for athletics more seriously, and so she recommended me to [coach] Melvin Tan." (wings.org.sg, 03 Mar 2014)'), ('Coach', 'Melvin Tan [national] (myactivesg.com, 09 Jan 2018)'), ('Training', 'As part of her training she incorporates traditional Chinese medicine treatments, which can include acupuncture, massages and cupping. "I was a bit apprehensive about trying traditional Chinese medicine because I hadn\'t heard much about it, but I trusted my coach who recommended it. The treatments help to loosen tight muscles and prevent injury." (herworld.com, 15 Aug 2016)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralSPRINT FOCUSShe says she is most comfortable competing in shorter sprint events. "The process of running a 100m dash intrigues me as so much mechanics is involved in a 12-second race. I\'ve also been running the 100m ever since I started athletics, so I\'m most comfortable with it. Regarding the 400m and 800m distances, I am not sure if my endurance levels will allow me to compete at the top levels for these distances." (wings.org.sg, 02 Sep 2014) '), ('Education', 'National University of Singapore, Singapore'), ('Languages', 'English'), ('Hobbies', 'Playing football, traditional Indian dancing. name: Zubin Percy
bio: [('Coach', 'Ron Helmer [club] (singaporeathletics.org.sg, 14 May 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralSINGAPORE TO UNITED STATESIn 2017 he received a partial athletics scholarship to study at the University of Indiana in Bloomington, ID, United States of America, where he is studying a degree in business. "Indiana is a Division I [NCAA] school, so I know I\'ll get the push that I need to get to the next level, which is really important to me. I\'ve been to the US on training stints [before]. You\'re competing against faster athletes and you\'re pushing yourself in every session." (straitstimes.com, 12 May 2017)MILITARY SERVICEHe did not participate in the 2017 South East Asian Games in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, as he was in the process of completing his national military service. "It\'s been tough [but] I\'ve enjoyed the process as a whole. I was given time off to train during National Service, for which I\'m extremely grateful." (pinoyathletics.info, 18 Jan 2018; straitstimes.com, 12 May 2017)OLD RECORD BROKENIn 2014 he broke a 40-year-old Singapore national record for the 400m event, while he was still a junior. He ran the distance in 47.29 seconds, beating the previous national record of 47.4 seconds set by Godfrey Jallah in 1974. (straitstimes.com, 17 Jun 2017) '), ('Injuries', 'In 2015 he sustained an injury to his hamstring two weeks prior to the 2015 South East Asian Games in Singapore. He was still able to participate in the competition. name: JUNG YI
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began learning to swim at age five at Warren Golf and Country Club in Singapore. (warren.org.sg, 01 Nov 2017)'), ('Coach', 'Stephan Widmer [national], AUS; Gary Tan [national], SGP (swimming.org.sg, 14 Jun 2018; swimmingworldmagazine.com, 18 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2018 Asian Games in Indonesia, the 2018 Youth Olympic Games in Buenos Aires, Argentina, and the Olympic Games. (warren.org.sg, 01 Nov 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralMOTIVATIONHe believes that competing at his first major championships, the 2017 South East Asian Games, was a major step in his swimming career. "It was both eye-opening and enriching. After racing at the Games, I came to realise that behind the many impressive races swam by the inspirational swimming legends are people who are not so different from normal swimmers, going through their routines before their races, working hard to achieve their dreams behind the scenes. While this may seem like it is a given, realising this fact was really an eye-opener for me, as someone who previously viewed their performances as otherworldly and even a little inaccessible. This gives me hope that I may one day be like them, performing perfect strokes and swimming record times. (warren.org.sg, 01 Nov 2017) '), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationResultSouth East Asian Games4200m Butterfly2017Kuala Lumpur, MAS2:01.16')]

name: JOAN XUE HUA
bio: [('Beginning', 'Having previously competed in dragon boat and sailing at international level, she began rowing in December 2014. (todayonline.com, 21 Oct 2017)'), ('Reason', 'One of her friends encouraged her to try the sport. "I could manage the training load because of my background in dragon boat and sailing. There are similarities between dragon boat and rowing as they are cyclical sports where you do the same movements over and over and try to achieve perfection. Maybe that\'s why sailing was not my thing, because it was tactical. I\'m more of an endurance sport athlete." (todayonline.com, 21 Oct 2017)'), ('Coach', 'John Holland, IRL (todayonline.com, 21 Oct 2017)'), ('Training', 'She trains nine times a week. (todayonline.com, 21 Oct 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (todayonline.com, 21 Oct 2017)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralMULTI TALENTEDHaving joined the Singapore national team for dragon boat in 2009, she went on to compete in the sport at the 2010 Asian Games in Guangzhou, People\'s Republic of China, and the 2011 South East Asian Games in Indonesia. She quit in 2012 so she could qualify as a nurse, but in 2013 one of her teammates from the dragon boat team signed her up for an athlete recruitment programme that was looking for potential sailors. She was selected to form a partnership with Dawn Liu, initially in the 470 class and then in the 49er FX class, but the pair missed out on qualification for the 2013 South East Asian Games. Liu also broke her hand at the 2014 World Championships in Santander, Spain, which meant they were unable to qualify for the 2016 Olympic Games. Days later the partnership ended. "I remember being very confused in the boat. I thought I was going to be a dead weight. Sailing is very tactical, I worked very hard in the boat but I had no idea what was going on in the race. I didn\'t find it very fulfilling. Dawn had sailed for decades and she was very experienced. We spent a lot of time on getting my feel of the boat, balance and keeling the boat at a certain degree," Poh said. (SportsDeskOnline, 19 Jul 2018; todayonline.com, 21 Oct 2017)ROWING REDEMPTIONShe began rowing in December 2014, just months after she had competed in sailing at the 2014 World Championships in Santander, Spain. Although she had to be rescued by motorboat the first time she went out on the reservoir after her rowing boat capsized, she managed to qualify for the 2015 South East Asian Games in Singapore, which took place just six months later, and went on to win a bronze medal at the event. (todayonline.com, 21 Oct 2017)OCCUPATIONShe is a registered nurse at Tan Tock Seng hospital in Singapore. (Facebook profile, 20 Nov 2017) '), ('Education', 'Nursing - Nanyang Polytechnic , Singapore'), ('Languages', 'English'), ('Highlights', 'ROWINGRankEventYearLocationResultAsian Championships7Single Sculls2017Pattaya, THA8:03.75South East Asian Games3Pair 1000m2015Singapore3:48.184Pair 500m2015Singapore1:42.18TRADITIONAL BOAT RACINGRankEventYearLocationResultAsian Games4Canoe TBR 250m2010Guangzhou, CHN1:03.2934Canoe TBR 500m2010Guangzhou, CHN2:11.8325Canoe TBR 1000m2010Guangzhou, CHN4:27.233SAILINGRankEventYearLocationISAF World Championships5549er FX2014Santander, ESP')]

name: ALLA

name: TING WEN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began swimming classes at age five. (olympic.org, 2018; myactivesg.com, 18 Jul 2017)'), ('Injuries', 'She was struggling with a shoulder injury during the 2018 Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast, QLD, Australia. The injury started to bother her in 2017. (straitstimes.com, 08 Apr 2018)In November 2011 she broke two bones in her arm in a surfing accident when a surfboard hit her after a big wave. The injury required surgery, with two metal plates and 15 screws inserted in her arm. The injury stopped her from swimming for six weeks and she did not regain full use of her arm for three months. The time out meant she was unable to qualify for the 2012 Olympic Games in London. name: ZHENG WEN
bio: [('Beginning', "He learned to swim at age six at his father's swimming club. He began competing at age 12. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016; teamsingapore.com.sg, 08 Nov 2011)"), ('Reason', '"Since I was little I have enjoyed going to the beach and playing in the water. It was only natural for my parents to sign me up for swimming lessons, just so I would be water safe. I continued to swim on a regular basis because my older sister was a competitive swimmer. It was then I realised I enjoyed racing." name: JOSEPH ISAAC
bio: [('Beginning', 'He learned to swim at age four. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Reason', 'His talent was spotted at an early age and he was given the opportunity of attending the private Bolles School swimming institution in Jacksonville, FL, United States of America. "My parents wanted me to [learn to swim], because Singapore is surrounded by water. I enjoyed swimming so much. When they put me under the water I wasn\'t afraid, unlike other kids. I just used to giggle and found I really liked being in the water." (foxsports asia.com, 30 Mar 2016; prischew.com, 19 Nov 2013)'), ('Debut', '2011 for Singapore (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Coach', 'Stephan Widmer [national], AUS; Gary Tan [national], SGP (swimming.org.sg, 14 Jun 2018; swimmingworldmagazine.com, 18 Jul 2018)'), ('Ambition', 'To break the world record in the 100m butterfly. (swimswam.com, 15 Jun 2017)'), ('Awards', "In 2014 and 2016 he was named The Straits Times Athlete of the Year in Singapore. (swimswam.com, 20 Feb 2017, 05 Mar 2015)He was voted the 2015 Men's Swimmer of the Year by the Big 12 Conference in the United States of America. (texassports.com, 19 Apr 2016)He was named the 2014 Swimmer of the Year by the Singapore Swimming Association [SSA]. (todayonline.com, 26 Apr 2015) He was named the 2012 Sportsman of the Year at the Singapore Sports Awards. At age 16, he was the youngest person to have won the award. (yahoo.com, 30 May 2012)"), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first athlete from Singapore to win a gold medal at the Olympic Games when he triumphed in the 100m butterfly at the 2016 Games in Rio de Janeiro. He beat his idol Michael Phelps to claim the title. (ONS, 14 Aug 2016)RIO BLUESHe admitted that he got distracted from the sport in the months after winning gold in the 100m butterfly at the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. "Having so much attention, and on such a large scale, can definitely be overwhelming, and you can definitely lose yourself. That was where I was from August to December [in 2016]. Now, I tell myself, \'Keep doing well, accomplish what you want to do. All the opportunities will come and you can enjoy them when you\'re done with swimming\'." (swimswam.com, 15 Jun 2017)DEFERRED MILITARY TIMEIn October 2013 the Singapore government agreed he could delay his national service until August 2016, which would allow him to focus on training ahead of the 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro. In August 2016 it was announced his deferment had been extended until after the 2020 Games in Tokyo. "I\'m doing this because I love my country. I want to bring pride and glory to my country. If you ask me if swimming itself is a form of national service, I couldn\'t answer that question. It\'s not up to me. My job is to swim." (straitstimes.com, 15 Aug 2016; yahoo.com, 02 Dec 2013; straitstimes.com, 21 Oct 2013) '), ('Hero', 'US swimmer Michael Phelps. (todayonline.com, 04 Jun 2016)'), ('Influence', 'His parents. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Relatives', 'His uncle Lloyd Valberg represented Singapore in athletics at the 1948 Olympic Games in London. (SportsDeskOnline, 28 Apr 2015; straitstimes.com, 24 Sep 2014)'), ('Nickname', 'Jo (swimswam.com, 29 Mar 2016)'), ('Injuries', 'He competed at the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, despite suffering from nerve damage in his right shoulder. (asiaone.com, 24 Sep 2014)He suffered a sprained ankle in 2012. name: XIANG WEI JASMINE
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began shooting at age 13 in school. (Athlete, 03 Aug 2016)'), ('Reason', 'She was encouraged to take up the sport by her sister. name: CALVIN TECK KWANG
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began mountain biking at age 15 and took up road cycling two years later. (cranksmart.com, 23 Oct 2017; rockthenakedtruth.com, 14 Oct 2017)'), ('Reason', '"I started mountain biking initially because it gave me the freedom to explore Singapore, know the place better, and eat good food." (cranksmart.com, 23 Oct 2017)'), ('Awards', 'In 2018 he was named a Sports Excellence Scholar [spexScholars] at the spexScholarship Awards Presentation Ceremony in Singapore. (prischew.com, 21 Mar 2018)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralROAD TO TRACK CYCLING He represented Singapore in cycling road at the start of his international career, competing at the Asian championships and the South East Asian Games in 2009. He completed his national service between 2011 and 2013, before deciding to focus on cycling track in 2014. "For road cycling, in order to be competitive, you need a team of at least four or five people around you in order to get a good result. On the track, it requires a smaller team. A smaller team meant that we could travel around more easily while keeping expenses to a minimum. Also, Singapore always had a better medal record on the track than on the road." (cranksmart.com, 23 Oct 2017; rockthenakedtruth.com, 14 Oct 2017)LANDMARK VICTORYHe became the first male Singaporean athlete in 20 years to win gold in cycling track at the South East Asian Games when he triumphed in omnium at the 2107 Games in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. Singapore\'s last gold medal in cycling track had come at the 1997 Games in Jakarta, Indonesia, where Bernard Wong finished top of the podium in the points race. (straitstimes.com, 28 Aug 2017) '), ('Nickname', 'Chi Chi (davison.com.sg, 27 Nov 2017)'), ('Languages', 'English'), ('Highlights', 'RankEventYearLocationWorld Cup (Ranking)36Points Race2016/2017World CupDNFPoints Race2016/2017Apeldoorn, NEDAsian Championships7Madison2015Nakhon Ratchasima, THA8Omnium2015Nakhon Ratchasima, THA10Scratch2016Izu, JPN11Team Pursuit2017New Delhi, IND12Points Race2017New Delhi, IND14Scratch2017New Delhi, INDDNFPoints Race2018Nilai, MASDNFMadison2018Nilai, MASDNFPoints Race2016Izu, JPNSouth East Asian Games1Omnium2017Kuala Lumpur, MAS9Scratch2017Kuala Lumpur, MASDNFTeam Pursuit2017Kuala Lumpur, MASUCI Ranking (as of 07 Aug 2018)67Omnium2018/2019159Points Race2018/2019261Scratch2018/2019')]

name: Suat Li Michelle
bio: [('Beginning', 'She first tried the sport at school in Singapore. (mothership.sg, 17 Jan 2018)'), ('Reason', '"I fell in love with this sport because of the thrill it gives me when I soar across the bar." (myactivesg.com, 24 Aug 2017)'), ('Training', 'She trains at Kallang Practice Track in Singapore. (mothership.sg, 17 Jan 2018)'), ('Memorable', 'Winning the bronze medal in high jump at the 2015 South East Asian Games in Singapore. (todayonline.com, 13 Jun 2015)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralLONG WAITHer gold medal in high jump at the 2017 South East Asian Games in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, was Singapore\'s first female high jump gold medal for 52 years. She had finished the event tied for first-place with Vietnam\'s Duong Thi Viet Anh, and the pair had agreed to share the gold medal. However, the organisers later informed them that the gold could not be shared, and a jump-off was required. Viet Anh won the jump-off, but Singapore appealed and the original decision to share the gold was upheld. (mothership.sg, 17 Jan 2018; thestar.com.my, 26 Aug 2017)OTHER ACTIVITIESIn 2016 she co-founded Singapore High Jump, an organisation with the aim of supporting and promoting high jump in Singapore. "You see the sprinters all the time, and everything is a bit more flashy. We were trying to promote the event, and show others that high jump is not that quiet. It\'s nice to be recognised. It\'s an individual sport, so I thought it would be good for everyone to get together and be a bit closer." (mothership.sg, 17 Jan 2018; Singapore High Jump Facebook page, 06 Jun 2018)RETIREMENT AND RETURNShe retired from the sport in 2011 after struggling with a stress fracture injury she first sustained in 2007. She was convinced to return to training in November 2013 by her former coach Chan See Huey with a view to competing at the 2015 South East Asian Games in Singapore. (mothership.sg, 17 Jan 2018; straitstimes.com, 03 Jul 2017; singaporeathletics.org.sg, 04 Jun 2015) '), ('Nickname', 'High Jump Mama (mothership.sg, 17 Jan 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'She suffered a stress fracture to her left shin in 2007. She underwent surgery in 2008 but the injury continued to trouble her and led to her retiring from the sport in 2011. (mothership.sg, 17 Jan 2018; straitstimes.com, 03 Jul 2017; singaporeathletics.org.sg, 04 Jun 2015)'), ('Education', 'Business Management - Singapore Management University, Singapore, SGP'), ('Languages', 'English, Mandarin'), ('Hobbies', 'Travelling, yoga. name: YOKE LAN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began playing bridge in 1981. (doc.bridgebase.com, 12 Jan 2011)'), ('Reason', 'She was introduced to the sport by a friend while living in Chinese Taipei in 1981. "I loved it immediately. Bridge isn\'t all about yourself. You have to understand others as well." (sg.news.yahoo.com, 20 Nov 2011; doc.bridgebase.com, 12 Jan 2011)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTIn 2011 she became the first athlete from Singapore [alongside partner Seet Choon Cheng] to win a gold medal in bridge at a South East Asian Games. (singaporeolympics.com, 17 Apr 2015; sportsingapore.gov.sg, 02 Feb 2012)SACRIFICEIn 2011, she chose to compete in the South East Asian [SEA] Games in Indonesia and postponed her chemotherapy treatment for breast cancer. "I had to take part in the SEA Games because I was already committed to my bridge partner and the team. It wouldn\'t have been nice to do otherwise. My husband and family have been very supportive of my decision. My daughter was not happy at first but later on she was OK with it." (sg.news.yahoo.com, 20 Nov 2011)DONATING WINNINGSShe donated the winnings from her victory in the women\'s open pairs event at the 2011 South East Asian Games to the Singapore Contract Bridge Association [SCBA]. "I want to donate my money to SCBA so that they can use it to help promote contract bridge among younger Singaporeans." (sportsingapore.gov.sg, 02 Feb 2012) '), ('Highlights', "RankEventYearLocationWorld Bridge Games9Open Team Seniors2012Lille, FRA9Women's Team2008Beijing, CHN65Open Team2004Istanbul, TURWorld Bridge Series Championships18Open Team Seniors2014Sanya, CHNWorld Team Championships18Women's Team2005Estoril, PORSouth East Asian Games1Women's Pair2011Indonesia2Women's Team2011Indonesia2Mixed Pair2011Indonesia3Mixed Team2011Indonesia3Mixed Butler2011Indonesia10Women's Butler2011Indonesia")]

bio: [('Beginning', 'His parents enrolled him in a gymnastics class at about age five. (Team Media Guide, 27 Jul 2014)'), ('Debut', '2011 for Singapore, in Singapore (teamsingapore.com.sg, 01 Dec 2012)'), ('Coach', 'Ryosuke Kusumi [national], JPN (revolutionise.sg, 13 Jul 2018; myactivesg.com, 15 Feb 2018)'), ('Awards', 'He received the Singapore Sports Meritorious Award in 2012. name: SAMANTHA LOUISA GINN
bio: [('Beginning', 'She began swimming at age five. (teamsingapore.com.sg, 08 Nov 2011)'), ('Reason', '"I remember winning my first ever medal, a silver, at a group meet for the 21m backstroke and that is the exact moment I fell in love with the sport." (Team Media Guide, 28 Jul 2014)'), ('Coach', 'Stephan Widmer [national], AUS; Gary Tan [national], SGP (swimming.org.sg, 14 Jun 2018; swimmingworldmagazine.com, 18 Jul 2018)'), ('Awards', 'She received a Team Meritorious award at the 2012 Singapore Sports Awards. (singaporeolympics.com, 2013)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralWOLVERINEShe competed for the University of Michigan Wolverines from 2014 to 2018. She raced her last race for the Wolverines in March 2018 and enjoyed her time there. "I could not be more proud to be surrounded by such a grounded, determined, and inspiring group of individuals. It has truly been an honour to fight for the Block M [University of Michigan]. And while I have fallen short of some of my goals as my four years officially comes to a close, you all have made it so, so special. From our worst practises to our best races and everything in between, this team has showered me with countless memories that have strengthened me and will be with me for the rest of my life." (mgoblue.com, 01 Apr 2018; Instagram profile, 18 Mar 2018) '), ('Injuries', 'In October 2013 she dislocated her right knee after slipping during dry land training. name: ZHENGGANG
bio: [('Beginning', 'He began fencing at his school, Raffles Institution, in Singapore in 2004. (studentry.sg, 13 Nov 2012)'), ('Reason', 'He chanced upon some fencers who were training when he was a young boy, and his mother suggested he try it. When fencing became an extra-curricular activity at Raffles Institution he took it up through school. "As I have always loved combat sports since I was young, my mum thought that fencing would be a good choice for me. When I found out that it was offered as an activity in my school, I jumped right in." (myactivesg.com, 02 Jul 2014; studentry.sg, 13 Nov 2012; absolutefencing.com.sg, 01 Aug 2013)'), ('Debut', '2007 for Singapore (absolutefencing.com.sg, 01 Aug 2013)'), ('Coach', 'Wu Jie [club]; Wang Wenying [club] (Instagram profile, 16 Dec 2017)'), ('Ambition', 'To become one of the best fencers in the world and to compete at the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo. (vimeo.com, 17 Nov 2016; studentry.sg, 13 Nov 2012)'), ('Additional Information', 'GeneralCAREER LOWHe said that his 2014 knee injury provoked a difficult period in his career. "That was a low point in my fencing career because I had to undergo reconstructive surgery to repair my ACL and I missed out on the chance to fence at the SEA Games on home soil in Singapore in 2015. [But] I thought to myself that the injury is just a minor setback, and I can get back on my feet to compete for higher levels." (vimeo.com, 17 Nov 2016)COACHINGIn addition to competing, he also holds Singapore Coaching Council qualifications. He is an assistant coach at school fencing clinics as well as at the Singapore School of Science and Technology. "Fencing has inspired me in many aspects of my life. I have learnt to be confident, to carry myself with pride and stand up bravely in times of need. It also taught me how to react fast to changing situations. I hope I can pass on these values to my friends in school." (absolutefencing.com.sg, 01 Aug 2013; studentry.sg, 13 Nov 2012) '), ('Influence', 'His coaches. (absolutefencing.com.sg, 01 Aug 2013)'), ('Relatives', 'His wife Goh Wanqi represented Singapore in fencing until 2015, and won gold at the 2014 Commonwealth Championships in Largs, Scotland. (absolutefencing.com.sg, 19 Sep 2014; FIE, 2018)'), ('Injuries', 'In 2014 he tore the left anterior cruciate ligament in his knee when he slipped during a match. The injury required surgery, and as a result he was unable to compete at the 2015 South East Asian Games in Singapore. (vimeo.com, 17 Nov 2016; straitstines.com, 17 Jul 2016)'), ('Education', 'National University of Singapore, Singapore'), ('Languages', 'English'), ('Hobbies', 'Basketball, football.
